		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>I'll say this again, more clearly this time:</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I thought mage pets were supposed to be used in conjunction with mage casting.&nbsp; Meaning, mage sic's a pet on a target, pet does some minor damage, pet effects go off maybe rooting, stunning, or interrupting the other player, mage starts casting his damage spells against the target.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>From the complaints it seems like the Mages want a pet that can solo&nbsp;any other class, or at least do the majority of damage against a player, and if that's the case, nuhuh, no way.&nbsp; If a pet does more than 20% of the damage it's over powered in my mind.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I think what Barm is saying is that it sounds like your test was against the best possibly equiped&nbsp;opponents you could find, and did poorly.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>How's about you find an averagely equiped rogue, one in a mix of some ornate chain, maybe some VT, and a few GoD or OoW pieces and THEN see how well the pet does.&nbsp; You'll probably find the pet does closer to 20% total damage on its melee target before it dies.&nbsp; Then do the same thing with a similarly equiped caster and then see how well it does.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I don't think there's a problem with mage pets, they are effective in how I've seen them used, mainly as a means to prevent the mage from having to receive damage from a target.&nbsp; Casters can't cast while interrupted, melee's can't melee while rooted/stunned...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I want some more "realistic" tests before I'll agree there's a real problem with mage pets.</DIV>
